ion, and a richer cycling culture than anywhere else in the world. Evan Friss unearths the hidden history of the cycling city, demonstrating that diverse groups of cyclists managed to remap cities with new roads, paths, and laws, challenge social conventions, and even dream up a new urban ideal inspired by the bicycle. When cities were chaotic and filthy, bicycle advocates imagined an improved landscape in which pollution was negligible, transportation was silent and rapid, leisure spaces were democratic, and the divisions between city and country were blurred. Friss argues that when the utopian vision of a cycling city faded by the turn of the century, its death paved the way for today’s car-centric cities—and ended the prospect of a true American cycling city ever being built.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCyclingzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aUrban transportationzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aurban, city, transportation, mobility, gender, technology, invention, freedom, bicycles, cycling, commuting, infrastructure, pollution, leisure, science, recreation, health, progress, utopia, reform, activism, road, nonfiction, history, planning, poverty, wealth, class, travel, nature, youth, invigoration, immigration, noise, land use, parks, development, sports, sociology, politics, clubs, bike paths, lobbying.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022621091940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226211077423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226211077/original  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069043-